      <hedline>
        <hl1>Protecting Religions</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Evan Keller Farber letter, commenting on Stephen L Carter's Sept 3 Op-Ed, says Sen Joseph I Lieberman can promote his ideas about religion in public life without scaring people the way the religious right does because he, being an Orthodox Jew, is a member of a religious minority</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Stephen L. Carter (Op-Ed, Sept. 3) argues that the founders adopted separation of church and state not to keep the government religion-free but to protect religion from government intrusion. He does not, however, take into account that the concern was for the protection of minority religious views.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Stephen L. Carter (Op-Ed, Sept. 3) argues that the founders adopted separation of church and state not to keep the government religion-free but to protect religion from government intrusion. He does not, however, take into account that the concern was for the protection of minority religious views.</p>
        <p>This helps explain why Senator Joseph I. Lieberman can promote his religious agenda with minimal opposition, while the evangelical movement can't. That movement scares people because it pushes a religious agenda as the Moral Majority; Mr. Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, is identified with a religious minority.</p>
        <p>It may be paradoxical that Senator Lieberman is joining evangelicals in promoting religion in the public sphere, but it is a testament to the separation doctrine that he is able to.</p>
        <p>EVAN KELLER FARBER  New Rochelle, N.Y., Sept. 4, 2000</p>
      </block>
